"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 13–15
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1chronicles-13-15.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1chronicles.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1chronicles.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch13: ark transport failure — Uzza as negative type (wrong approach to holiness);
  Christ as the mediator who absorbs the breach; 3-month blessing at Obed-edom
- Ch14: David's divine consultation pattern = type of Christ's dependence on the Father (John 5:19);
  Baal-perazim = Christ who breaks through the powers (Col 2:15);
  Nathan son of David = Luke 3:31 Messianic genealogical line
- Ch15: the proper Levitical approach = shadow of Christ the one mediator (1 Tim 2:5);
  David in priestly linen = type of priest-king Melchizedek fulfilled in Christ (Heb 7);
  Michal's contempt = contempt for humble incarnate Christ (Isa 53:3)
- Seven priests with trumpets (15:24) = prefigure the seven eschatological trumpets (Rev 8-11)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON1 = {
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>David&rsquo;s opening act is consultation — with commanders, leaders, and the whole assembly. As a theme, this servant-leadership prefigures Christ&rsquo;s own practice: the Son who does nothing of his own initiative but acts in concert with the Father and for the benefit of his people (John 5:19). The Davidic king who leads by wisdom and consent, not coercion, traces the outline of the king who would come not to be served but to serve (Mark 10:45).</p>',
    "2": '<p>&lsquo;If it seems good to you, and if it is of the LORD our God&rsquo; — David conditions the mission on both communal assent and divine will. As a theme: the Messianic king seeks consensus and divine sanction simultaneously. Christ embodies this fully — never acting apart from the Father&rsquo;s will (&lsquo;not my will, but yours&rsquo;, Luke 22:42) yet also gathering his people into the mission. The ark project is framed as something for &lsquo;our brothers who remain in all the land of Israel&rsquo; — the whole people of God brought together.</p>',
    "3": '<p>&lsquo;We did not inquire of the ark in the days of Saul.&rsquo; Saul&rsquo;s failure to seek YHWH is explicitly named as the problem David is correcting. This failure of Saul — the first anointed (messiah) king — is the shadow of all human kingship unaided by God. The true Messiah will not fail to seek the Father: Christ&rsquo;s prayer life is the pattern of the king who constantly inquires (Luke 6:12; John 11:41-42). The correction David seeks is the one Christ embodies permanently.</p>',
    "4": '<p>&lsquo;The thing seemed right in the eyes of all the people.&rsquo; The universal assent of the assembly fulfills the pattern of the king whose purposes align with the people&rsquo;s true good. As a theme, this anticipates the NT vision of the Messianic community — &lsquo;the whole group of those who believed were of one heart and soul&rsquo; (Acts 4:32). The unity of Israel around the ark project is a temporal image of the unity of the church around the risen Christ.</p>',
    "5": '<p>&lsquo;From Shihor of Egypt to the entrance of Hamath&rsquo; — the ideal geographical scope of all Israel assembling. The gathering of all Israel around the ark foreshadows the eschatological gathering of all God&rsquo;s people around the risen Christ. Isaiah 56:8: &lsquo;The Lord GOD, who gathers the outcasts of Israel, declares, I will gather yet others to him besides those already gathered.&rsquo; The ark procession anticipates the final procession of all nations toward the city of God (Rev 21:24).</p>',
    "6": '<p>The ark had been in Kiriath-jearim — in exile from its appointed place, since the Philistines captured it (1 Sam 5). As a type, the ark&rsquo;s displacement from its home and its return under David images the return of the divine presence after the long exile of sin. Christ is the permanent ark — the dwelling of God with humanity — who after apparent defeat (cross) returns in glory. John 1:14: &lsquo;the Word became flesh and &lsquo;tabernacled&rsquo; among us.&rsquo;</p>',
    "7": '<p>The &lsquo;new cart&rsquo; was the Philistine method — borrowed from the enemy, not commanded by YHWH. As a shadow, the new cart represents approaching God on human terms rather than God&rsquo;s appointed terms. Christ&rsquo;s words in John 14:6 (&lsquo;I am the way, the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me&rsquo;) are the permanent theological claim that there is only one appointed approach to God — not a self-devised shortcut, however well-intentioned.</p>',
    "8": '<p>&lsquo;David and all Israel were celebrating before God with all their might.&rsquo; Genuine celebration with improper form — the problem is not the devotion but the method. As a theme, this verse encapsulates the NT distinction between sincere worship and worship in spirit and truth (John 4:23-24). Christ teaches that the Father seeks worshippers who worship both genuinely (<em>and</em> according to the truth he has established). Sincerity alone is insufficient; truth alone is cold; both together is the New Covenant worship.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Uzza reached out to steady the ark when the oxen stumbled. The instinct was protective; the act was fatal. As a type of the holiness problem, this verse establishes that divine holiness cannot be approached by even the best human impulse without proper mediation. Hebrews 10:19-22 presents Christ as the solution: &lsquo;we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus, by the new and living way that he opened for us.&rsquo; Uzza reached out without that way; Christ opened it.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The divine anger against Uzza is the clearest statement of the ark narrative&rsquo;s Christological problem: God&rsquo;s holiness is fatal to unauthorized human contact. The NT does not soften this — Heb 12:28-29: &lsquo;let us offer to God acceptable worship, with reverence and awe, for our God is a consuming fire.&rsquo; What changes in Christ is not God&rsquo;s holiness but the provision of mediation: the high priest who entered the Most Holy Place once for all (Heb 9:12) absorbs the barrier between God&rsquo;s fire and his people.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Perez-uzza (&lsquo;breach of Uzza&rsquo;) — the <em>pereṣ</em> of divine holiness breaking against unauthorized approach. The same root appears in 14:11 (Baal-perazim), where the breach runs the other direction against Israel&rsquo;s enemies. As a shadow, both point to Christ as the one who absorbs the breach: &lsquo;God made him who knew no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&rsquo; (2 Cor 5:21). The breaking out that should fall on us fell on him.</p>',
    "12": '<p>&lsquo;How can I bring the ark of God to me?&rsquo; David&rsquo;s fear is the right theological response to encountering the dangerous holiness of God. The question is the one every person must answer: how does sinful humanity approach a holy God? The answer in Chronicles is: through the proper Levitical mediation appointed by God. The NT answer is the same principle applied to its final fulfillment: through Christ the great high priest (&lsquo;let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace&rsquo;, Heb 4:16).</p>',
    "13": '<p>The ark diverted to the house of Obed-edom the Levite. The three-month pause while David learns the proper procedure is itself a type of the way God prepares the way for his own proper coming. Christ&rsquo;s coming was not improvised — the &lsquo;fullness of time&rsquo; (Gal 4:4) required centuries of preparation. The ark resting with Obed-edom is a pause in the forward movement of the divine presence — not abandonment but preparation for the proper arrival.</p>',
    "14": '<p>&lsquo;The LORD blessed the household of Obed-edom and everything he had.&rsquo; The ark&rsquo;s presence brings blessing to its host. As a type, this prefigures the blessing that flows from the indwelling presence of Christ: &lsquo;abide in me, and I in you … the branch cannot bear fruit by itself&rsquo; (John 15:4-5). The three months of blessing at Obed-edom&rsquo;s house is the small-scale version of the blessing that flows from the permanent dwelling of Christ with his people (Rev 21:3-4).</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>Hiram king of Tyre sends cedar timber, stonemasons, and carpenters to build David&rsquo;s palace. As a theme, the recognition of David&rsquo;s kingship by the nations anticipates the recognition of Christ as king. The Magi came from the east to honor the newborn king (Matt 2:2); Pilate wrote &lsquo;King of the Jews&rsquo; over the cross (John 19:19). Even those outside the covenant recognize the divinely appointed king — the Davidic pattern fulfilled in the one whom even pagan rulers are compelled to acknowledge.</p>',
    "2": '<p>&lsquo;David perceived that the LORD had established him as king over Israel and that his kingdom was highly exalted for the sake of his people Israel.&rsquo; The Davidic king understands his exaltation as covenantal and missional — for the people, not for himself. As a revelation of God: the God who exalts kings does so for the benefit of his people. The NT applies this to Christ: his exaltation to God&rsquo;s right hand is &lsquo;for us&rsquo; — he intercedes (Rom 8:34), sends the Spirit (Acts 2:33), and will bring his people to be where he is (John 14:3).</p>',
    "3": '<p>David took more wives and fathered more sons and daughters in Jerusalem. The dynasty expands at its Jerusalem center. As a theme, the multiplication of David&rsquo;s house points toward the ultimate heir through whom the dynasty will be fulfilled. The NT genealogies trace specific lines (Matthew through Solomon; Luke through Nathan) to show how the many sons of David converge on one Son of David. The expansion recorded here is the necessary background for the genealogical narrowing that eventually reaches Christ.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Among David&rsquo;s sons: Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon. Nathan (third in the list) is the ancestor of Mary&rsquo;s lineage of Christ in Luke 3:31 — the non-royal, non-Solomonic line through which the Messiah actually came into the world. The naming of Nathan in this list establishes the genealogical line even as the Chronicler focuses on Solomon (the temple-builder). The two Messianic genealogies diverge here at David&rsquo;s Jerusalem sons: Matthew traces Joseph&rsquo;s legal line through Solomon; Luke traces Mary&rsquo;s biological line through Nathan.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Ibhar, Elishua, Elpelet — three more of David&rsquo;s sons, whose names include theophoric elements (<em>ʾēl</em>, God). The expansion of the Davidic house with God-bearing names reflects the theological identity of the royal line: this is the family through whom God will accomplish his purposes. The theme: David&rsquo;s household is not merely a political dynasty but the vehicle of the covenant promise, expanding outward toward the one in whom all these names find their referent — &lsquo;God with us&rsquo; (Matt 1:23).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Nogah, Nepheg, Japhia — three more sons. The Davidic genealogy continues its expansion. Each name is a branch that the NT genealogists navigate to trace the Messianic line. As a theme: even the branches that are not the direct Messianic line are part of the Davidic family that establishes Christ&rsquo;s dynastic credentials. &lsquo;He will be great and will be called the Son of the Most High. And the Lord God will give to him the throne of his father David&rsquo; (Luke 1:32).</p>',
    "7": '<p>Elishama, Beeliada, Eliphelet. As a theme, these sons complete the roster of David&rsquo;s Jerusalem-born children. The Chronicler notes Beeliada (retaining the Baal-theophoric form where 2 Sam 5:16 has Eliada) — reflecting historical accuracy even in uncomfortable details. The revelation of God: divine history does not sanitize its instruments; the Davidic house includes sons with names honoring other gods, yet the covenant proceeds. Christ was &lsquo;made in human likeness&rsquo; (Phil 2:7) — he entered the fullness of human genealogical complexity.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The Philistines come against David when they hear he is anointed king over all Israel. As a type, the hostile response of the powers to the anointed king mirrors the response of the spiritual powers to Christ&rsquo;s anointing. At Christ&rsquo;s baptism (&lsquo;This is my beloved Son&rsquo;, Matt 3:17), the wilderness temptation follows immediately. Revelation 12:4-5 depicts the dragon waiting to devour the royal child. The pattern: the anointed one provokes the opposition of the powers by his very appointment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The Philistines spread out in the Valley of Rephaim (the valley of the ancient giants, southwest of Jerusalem). As a shadow, the enemies gathering in the valley of the giants at the approach of the anointed king images the gathering of the powers against Christ. Acts 4:26-27 quotes Psalm 2 (&lsquo;the kings of the earth took their stand … against the LORD and against his anointed&rsquo;) and applies it to the gathering against Jesus: &lsquo;for truly in this city there were gathered together against your holy servant Jesus … Herod and Pontius Pilate.&rsquo;</p>',
    "10": '<p>&lsquo;David inquired of God.&rsquo; This is the type: the king who only acts after seeking the Father. John 5:19 is the NT fulfillment in Christ: &lsquo;The Son can do nothing of his own accord, but only what he sees the Father doing.&rsquo; John 5:30: &lsquo;I can do nothing on my own.&rsquo; David&rsquo;s inquiry before battle is the shadow of Christ&rsquo;s perfect dependence — the Davidic pattern made explicit in Christ who fulfills it perfectly. YHWH answers: &lsquo;Go up, for I will give them into your hand.&rsquo;</p>',
    "11": '<p>Baal-perazim — &lsquo;the Lord of the breakthroughs.&rsquo; David declares: &lsquo;God has broken through my enemies by my hand, like a breakthrough of waters.&rsquo; As a type, this breakthrough-victory anticipates Christ&rsquo;s resurrection — the ultimate breaking through. Death could not hold him (Acts 2:24); the gates of Hades could not prevail (Matt 16:18). The name Baal-perazim is reclaimed: not Baal but YHWH is the one who breaks through. Christ is the resurrection and the life who breaks through the ultimate barrier.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The Philistines abandoned their gods on the battlefield; David burned them. As a shadow, this anticipates Christ&rsquo;s victory over the powers: &lsquo;he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him&rsquo; (Col 2:15). The gods of the enemy are revealed as impotent — they were left behind by their own worshippers. Christ&rsquo;s cross exposes and defeats the principalities; the burning of the Philistine gods is the small-scale image of the definitive victory over all false gods.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A second Philistine incursion — the defeated enemy returns. As a theme, the persistence of opposition to the anointed king mirrors the persistence of opposition to Christ. After every apparent victory, the enemy regrouped. Christ himself warns of this: &lsquo;the thief comes only to steal and kill and destroy&rsquo; (John 10:10); the spirits return (Luke 11:24-26). The proper response is always renewed inquiry of God — not self-reliance based on prior success.</p>',
    "14": '<p>&lsquo;Do not go up after them; go around.&rsquo; God gives David a different tactical instruction for the second battle — the same enemy requires fresh dependence, not cached strategy. As a revelation of God: YHWH is not a formula but a living guide whose specific direction must be sought each time. Christ teaches the same principle: the Spirit &lsquo;will guide you into all the truth&rsquo; (John 16:13) — not a static set of rules but ongoing living guidance from the one who goes before.</p>',
    "15": '<p>&lsquo;When you hear the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees, then go out to battle, for God has gone out before you.&rsquo; The divine warrior going before his people — YHWH leading the battle — is the OT military theology. As a type, this prefigures Christ as the pioneer and perfecter (Heb 12:2: <em>archēgon</em>, the one who goes first, leads the way). Revelation 19:11-14 depicts Christ going before his armies on a white horse. The sound in the treetops is the advance movement of the one who always goes before.</p>',
    "16": '<p>&lsquo;David did as God commanded, and they struck down the Philistine army from Gibeon to Gezer.&rsquo; Obedience to specific divine word produces comprehensive victory. The scope (Gibeon to Gezer, a broad sweep clearing the western approaches) reflects the proportionality of the victory to the divine command followed. As a revelation of God: YHWH&rsquo;s specific commands, when fully followed, produce comprehensive results. Christ fulfills this in himself: &lsquo;I have come down from heaven not to do my own will but the will of him who sent me&rsquo; (John 6:38).</p>',
    "17": '<p>&lsquo;The LORD brought the fear of him upon all nations.&rsquo; David&rsquo;s fame through divine power echoes the covenant promise of Deut 28:10. As a revelation of God, this outcome points toward the Messianic prophecies of universal recognition: &lsquo;at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father&rsquo; (Phil 2:10-11). The fear that preceded the nations before the Davidic warrior becomes the ultimate submission before the Messianic king.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>David prepares a tent for the ark in the city of David. As a shadow, this prepared place anticipates the dwelling of God with his people that Christ establishes permanently. John 14:2-3: &lsquo;In my Father&rsquo;s house are many rooms … I go to prepare a place for you.&rsquo; David&rsquo;s preparation of space for the ark is the type of Christ&rsquo;s preparation of space for his people. The progression: tent → temple → Christ → New Jerusalem (Rev 21:3) traces the same trajectory of prepared divine dwelling.</p>',
    "2": '<p>&lsquo;No one ought to carry the ark of God except the Levites, for the LORD chose them.&rsquo; The shadow: there is an appointed way of approach to God, not any way. This principle reaches its NT fulfillment in 1 Tim 2:5: &lsquo;there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus.&rsquo; The Levitical exclusivity for ark-bearing is the shadow of Christ&rsquo;s exclusive mediation — not as arbitrary rule but as the divine provision of the one true and sufficient approach.</p>',
    "3": '<p>&lsquo;David assembled all Israel at Jerusalem&rsquo; — the third great gathering around the ark in Chronicles (ch13 first; ch15 second and successful). As a theme, the gathering of all Israel around the ark prefigures the eschatological gathering of all God&rsquo;s people around Christ. John 11:52: Christ would die &lsquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad.&rsquo; The Jerusalem assembly is the temporal image of the eternal assembly of the church (Heb 12:22-23).</p>',
    "4": '<p>&lsquo;David brought together the sons of Aaron and the Levites.&rsquo; The assembly of priests and Levites is a type of the gathered priestly community. The NT declares that all believers are &lsquo;a royal priesthood&rsquo; (1 Pet 2:9) — the entire people of God gathered to serve in the presence of Christ. This verse&rsquo;s assembling of sacred servants at Jerusalem is the foreshadowing of the gathering of the whole priestly people around the throne of God and the Lamb (Rev 1:6; 5:10).</p>',
    "5": '<p>Kohath (Uriel, 120 kinsmen) — the most honored Levitical clan, charged with carrying the most sacred objects. As a theme, the Kohathite priority reflects the principle that those who carry the holy presence bear a special weight and responsibility. Christ is not merely served by ministers — he is the one carried in the hearts of his people (Col 1:27: &lsquo;Christ in you, the hope of glory&rsquo;). The honor given to the Kohathites who bore the ark points to the dignity of bearing Christ to the world.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Merari (Asaiah, 220 kinsmen) — charged with the tabernacle&rsquo;s structural framework in the wilderness. As a theme, the different Levitical clans with their different sacred responsibilities prefigure the diversity of gifts within the one body: &lsquo;there are different kinds of gifts, but the same Spirit; different kinds of service, but the same Lord&rsquo; (1 Cor 12:4-5). The organized division of Levitical labor images the organized diversity of the church&rsquo;s ministry around the one Christ they serve.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Gershom (Joel, 130 kinsmen) — the firstborn Levitical clan, subordinate in sacred function despite primogeniture. As a theme, the inversion of birth order in sacred priority (Gershom the eldest, yet Kohath bears the holiest objects) runs throughout Scripture and reaches its culmination in Christ: &lsquo;the last will be first, and the first will be last&rsquo; (Matt 20:16). The Gershomite subordination in the Levitical hierarchy reflects the divine preference for inversion of natural priority.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Elizaphan (Shemaiah, 200 kinsmen) — a Kohathite subclan with significant numbers. As a theme, the comprehensive mobilization of all Levitical clans for the ark procession images the full engagement of the whole body of Christ in worship. Revelation 5:11-12 describes &lsquo;myriads of myriads and thousands of thousands, saying with loud voice, &ldquo;Worthy is the Lamb who was slain, to receive power and wealth and wisdom and might and honor and glory and blessing.&rdquo;&rsquo; The organized Levitical choir is the small-scale image of the great heavenly multitude.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Hebron (Eliel, 80 kinsmen) — another Kohathite subclan. The city of Hebron was the site of David&rsquo;s first anointing as king over Judah (2 Sam 2:4) and later over all Israel (2 Sam 5:3); it was also the burial place of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob (Gen 23; 25:9; 49:31). The Hebron clan participating in the ark procession connects the founding patriarchal covenant site to the Davidic covenant moment. The whole Abrahamic-Davidic covenant line is present in this procession — a procession pointing to the one who fulfills both covenants.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Uzziel (Amminadab, 112 kinsmen) — the fourth Kohathite subclan. The six Levitical groups total 862 men assembled for one sacred act. As a revelation of God: YHWH cares about the proper ordering of worship, not merely its occurrence. The detailed organization reflects what Paul articulates for New Covenant worship: &lsquo;let all things be done decently and in order&rsquo; (1 Cor 14:40). Order in worship honors the holiness of the one being worshipped — whether at the ark or at the throne of Christ.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Zadok and Abiathar, the two rival priestly lines, serve together under David. The tension between them (resolved when Solomon expels Abiathar in 1 Kgs 2:27) is a shadow of the priestly ambiguity that Christ permanently resolves. Hebrews 7:11-12 argues that the Levitical priesthood was temporary and incomplete — &lsquo;if perfection had been attainable through the Levitical priesthood, what further need would there have been for another priest to arise after the order of Melchizedek?&rsquo; Christ is the one high priest who makes the Zadok/Abiathar tension obsolete.</p>',
    "12": '<p>&lsquo;Sanctify yourselves.&rsquo; The call to priestly self-purification before handling the holy ark. As a shadow, this points to the purification Christ accomplishes for his people: &lsquo;for their sake I consecrate myself, that they also may be sanctified in truth&rsquo; (John 17:19). Christ does not merely call his people to purify themselves; he sanctifies himself on their behalf so that they can approach what is holy. The Levites purify themselves; Christ purifies his people by his own self-offering.</p>',
    "13": '<p>&lsquo;Because you Levites did not carry it the first time, the LORD our God broke out against us.&rsquo; David takes corporate responsibility for the disaster. As a revelation of God: the failure of those appointed to handle sacred things affects the whole community. Christ takes this to its ultimate expression by bearing corporate responsibility not for improper worship procedure but for the entire human failure before God. He is &lsquo;made sin&rsquo; for us (2 Cor 5:21) — bearing the whole corporate consequence so that the full approach to God can be restored.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The priests and Levites collectively sanctify themselves. The communal purification prepares the community for the presence of the holy God. As a theme, this anticipates the New Covenant purification of the whole people: &lsquo;he gave himself for us to redeem us from all lawlessness and to purify for himself a people for his own possession who are zealous for good works&rsquo; (Titus 2:14). The Levitical sanctification is the shadow of Christ&rsquo;s redemptive purification of his own people for his own dwelling.</p>',
    "15": '<p>&lsquo;The Levites carried the ark of God on their shoulders with the poles on it, as Moses had commanded.&rsquo; The triple citation of authority (Moses, word of the LORD) signals that the successful second attempt follows the divinely appointed pattern. As a shadow, this contrasts with the improvised first attempt and points to Christ who &lsquo;came not to abolish the Law and the Prophets but to fulfill them&rsquo; (Matt 5:17). Christ does not devise a new way; he perfectly fulfills the appointed way. The poles on shoulders, not the borrowed cart, is the image of appointed rather than improvised mediation.</p>',
    "16": '<p>David&rsquo;s instruction to appoint Levites as singers is the foundation of Israel&rsquo;s temple musical tradition. As a theme, the organized sung worship of YHWH points to the NT&rsquo;s sung worship of Christ: &lsquo;addressing one another in psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, singing and making melody to the Lord with your heart&rsquo; (Eph 5:19). Revelation 5:9 gives the ultimate image: the living creatures and elders &lsquo;sang a new song&rsquo; before the Lamb. David&rsquo;s appointment of Levitical singers is the institution; the song of the Lamb is its eternal fulfillment.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Heman, Asaph, and Ethan — the three founding temple musicians. Their psalms are addressed to God and sometimes explicitly Messianic: Psalm 88 (Heman) is the only psalm with no resolution, ending in darkness — which finds its answer only in Christ&rsquo;s cry of desolation (Ps 22; Matt 27:46) and resurrection. Psalm 89 (Ethan) celebrates the Davidic covenant: &lsquo;I will establish his offspring forever&rsquo; — a promise fulfilled in Christ (Luke 1:33). The temple musicians&rsquo; psalms are Messianic prophecy in song.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The second-rank Levitical musicians — eight names who serve under the three lead singers. As a theme, the graduated structure of temple music (lead singers and those in the second rank) mirrors the structure of the body of Christ where &lsquo;God has appointed in the church first apostles, second prophets, third teachers&rsquo; (1 Cor 12:28). The hierarchy is not about worth but about function — all serve the one worship of the one God. Christ is both the content of the worship and the one who appoints those who lead it.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Heman, Asaph, and Ethan appointed to sound bronze cymbals. Psalm 150:5 calls for &lsquo;resounding cymbals&rsquo; as praise — the same instruments here established as part of the founding musical appointment. As a theme, the percussion of the ark&rsquo;s procession anticipates the eschatological celebration described in Revelation 19:1-7: &lsquo;Hallelujah! Salvation and glory and power belong to our God.&rsquo; The temple cymbals announce the presence of YHWH; the heavenly voices announce the reign of the Lamb.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The <em>ʿal-ʿălāmôṯ</em> group plays lyres — the same term in Psalm 46&rsquo;s superscription (&lsquo;A Song of the Sons of Korah. According to <em>Alamoth</em>&rsquo;). Psalm 46 declares &lsquo;God is our refuge and strength&rsquo; and culminates: &lsquo;Be still, and know that I am God; I will be exalted among the nations, I will be exalted in the earth.&rsquo; The musical tradition here instituted carries psalms that the NT applies to Christ: his presence as the refuge of his people, his exaltation among all nations through the gospel (Phil 2:9-11).</p>',
    "21": '<p>The <em>ʿal-haššĕmînîṯ</em> group plays harps — the same term in Psalms 6 and 12&rsquo;s superscriptions. Psalm 6 is a lament for mercy (&lsquo;O LORD, heal me, for my bones are troubled&rsquo;) and Psalm 12 is a plea against the faithless (&lsquo;Save, O LORD, for the godly one is gone&rsquo;). These psalms of distress carry the voice of the sufferer that the NT hears as the voice of Christ in his humiliation. The musical modes established here are the vehicles for the lament psalms that anticipate the suffering Messiah.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Chenaniah, the chief musician, directed because he was &lsquo;skilled.&rsquo; As a revelation of God: sacred music requires genuine skill, not only enthusiasm. The appointment of the most skilled as chief reflects the principle that offering God one&rsquo;s best — trained, disciplined excellence — is itself an act of worship. Christ, described as one who &lsquo;learned obedience through what he suffered&rsquo; (Heb 5:8), embodies trained excellence applied to the most demanding sacred task: the sacrifice that opens the way to God.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Berechiah and Elkanah served as gatekeepers for the ark during transit. The gate-keeping role — controlling access to the sacred presence during the procession — is a shadow of Christ as the one who controls access to the Father: &lsquo;I am the gate; whoever enters through me will be saved&rsquo; (John 10:9). The two gatekeepers flanking the ark image the exclusive access-point that Christ establishes as the gate through whom the sheep enter and find safety.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Seven priests blow trumpets before the ark. Seven priests with trumpets echoes the Jericho narrative (Josh 6:4-6) and prefigures the seven trumpets of Revelation (Rev 8-11). The trumpets announce the presence and advance of YHWH: Jericho fell at the trumpet blast; the eschaton unfolds at the angel trumpets. The ark procession into Jerusalem with seven priests and trumpets is a liturgical enactment of what Revelation presents as eschatological reality — the advance of the divine presence that overthrows every obstacle. Christ&rsquo;s parousia is announced with the sound of the trumpet (1 Thess 4:16).</p>',
    "25": '<p>The elders and commanders go with David to bring up the ark. The same leadership assembly that initiated the project (ch13:1) now completes it. As a theme, the completion of worship is communal and involves the whole leadership of God&rsquo;s people. The NT vision of the church gathering for worship around the presence of Christ: &lsquo;where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them&rsquo; (Matt 18:20). The elder-led assembly around the ark is the type of the elder-surrounded throne in Revelation 4-5.</p>',
    "26": '<p>&lsquo;Because God helped (<em>ʿāzar</em>) the Levites.&rsquo; The successful transport is credited to divine assistance. As a revelation of God: even the divinely appointed and properly executed act of worship depends on divine help to succeed. Christ himself relied on divine strengthening: &lsquo;an angel from heaven appeared to him and strengthened him&rsquo; (Luke 22:43) in Gethsemane. The seven bulls and seven rams offered after the successful transport are the thank-offering of those who have received what they could not accomplish without God.</p>',
    "27": '<p>David wore a robe of fine linen — the priestly material. As a type, David dressed as both king and priest during the ark&rsquo;s installation anticipates Melchizedek, who was &lsquo;priest of God Most High&rsquo; and &lsquo;king of Salem&rsquo; simultaneously (Gen 14:18; Heb 7:1-3). Christ is explicitly identified as the Melchizedek-priest-king: &lsquo;you are a priest forever, after the order of Melchizedek&rsquo; (Ps 110:4; Heb 5:6). David&rsquo;s priestly attire in this royal procession is the shadow of Christ&rsquo;s eternal priest-king office.</p>',
    "28": '<p>&lsquo;All Israel brought up the ark of the covenant of the LORD with shouting (<em>tĕrûʿâ</em>), with the sound of the horn, trumpets, and cymbals, and with harps and lyres.&rsquo; The great communal procession with its full orchestra is the type of the great eschatological worship described in Revelation 7:9-12: &lsquo;Salvation belongs to our God who sits on the throne, and to the Lamb.&rsquo; The <em>tĕrûʿâ</em> shout connects to Ps 47:5 (&lsquo;God has gone up with a shout&rsquo;) and to the shout of Christ&rsquo;s return (1 Thess 4:16). The ark&rsquo;s processional shout is the liturgical seed of the eschatological shout.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Michal daughter of Saul looked down from the window and despised David dancing before the LORD. She is identified as &lsquo;daughter of Saul&rsquo; — the rejected dynasty looking down at the worshipping Davidic king. As a type, Michal&rsquo;s contempt for humble worship images the contempt for Christ&rsquo;s humility that Isaiah 53:3 predicts: &lsquo;he was despised and rejected by men.&rsquo; Those of the old order (Saulide; Pharisee; religious establishment) despised the humble worship of the one who truly honored God. The window image recalls Sisera&rsquo;s mother waiting for the wrong king&rsquo;s return — here the wrong dynasty watches the right king worship in humility.</p>'
  }
}

